pulltitle: Add Mozilla Code of Conduct
pullsbody:
As of January 1 2019, Mozilla requires that all GitHub projects include this [CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md](https://github.com/mozilla/repo-templates/blob/master/templates/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md) file in the project root. The file has two parts:

1. Required Text - All text under the headings *Community Participation Guidelines and How to Report*, are required, and should not be altered.
2. Optional Text - The Project Specific Etiquette heading provides a space to speak more specifically about ways people can work effectively and inclusively together. Some examples of those can be found on the [Firefox Debugger](https://github.com/devtools-html/debugger.html/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md) project, and [Common Voice](https://github.com/mozilla/voice-web/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md). (The optional part is commented out in the [raw template file](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mozilla/repo-templates/blob/master/templates/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md), and will not be visible until you modify and uncomment that part.)

If you have any questions about this file, or Code of Conduct policies and procedures, please see [Mozilla-GitHub-Standards](https://wiki.mozilla.org/GitHub/Repository_Requirements) or email Mozilla-GitHub-Standards+CoC@mozilla.com.

_(Message COC002)_
pull_commit_message:
See PR for details

_(Message COC002)_

pulltitle: Bug 1164878 - Allow users without an authenticated_email field to clo…
pullsbody:
…bber

The TokenUser is not anonymous, but also has no e-mail address associated with it.
When this combination occurs, a who value of 'automation' should be supplied, instead
of outright failing.

While not exact, the term automation gives us a way to categorize clobbers that seemed
to be authenticated by a permanent token (as opposed to a user token).
pull_commit_message:
Bug 1164878 - Allow users without an authenticated_email field to clobber

The TokenUser is not anonymous, but also has no e-mail address associated with it.
When this combination occurs, a who value of 'automation' should be supplied, instead
of outright failing.

While not exact, the term automation gives us a way to categorize clobbers that seemed
to be authenticated by a permanent token (as opposed to a user token).

pulltitle: All clobbers endpoints
pullsbody:
Two new endpoints, which allow one to get an overall view of what has been recently clobbered. Using these endpoints in tandem, you could build a manifest (with all) then update it periodically (using greater-than) to achieve branch agnostic bulk clobbers.

/clobberer/lastclobber/all
/clobberer/lastclobber/greater-than/<timestamp>
pull_commit_message:
Add endpoints which allow bulk viewing of clobber times

This will aid in batching clobbers.

pulltitle: Clobber logic
pull_commit_message:
Adds the ability to clobber specific slaves

The clobber endpoint now supports passing in a specific slave, when a slave is specified
only lastclobber queries with that slave will have access to its clobbertime. Otherwise,
when no slave is specified, a NULL value is passed to the clobber_times table and any
slave will have access to its data. That is, NULL acts as a wildcard for slaves.

pulltitle: Adds an endpoint which will always result in a clobber when accessed by ...
pullsbody:
...the client

Some builders are configured in such a way as to always require clobbering,
this is currently acheived by pointing them at the endpoint provided by:
https://github.com/mozilla/build-tools/blob/master/clobberer/always_clobber.php
Which simply returns a lastclobber time of the current time + one hour.
The forceclobber endpoint re-implements this behavior.
pull_commit_message:
Adds an endpoint which will always result in a clobber when accessed by the client

Some builders are configured in such a way as to always require clobbering,
this is currently acheived by pointing them at the endpoint provided by:
https://github.com/mozilla/build-tools/blob/master/clobberer/always_clobber.php
Which simply returns a lastclobber time of the current time + one hour.
The forceclobber endpoint re-implements this behavior.
